---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Crontinel vs Laravel Telescope: Different Tools, Different Jobs"
  description="Telescope is an indispensable debug tool. Crontinel is a monitoring and alerting tool. They're not competing, but one of them won't page you at 2am."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is this different from Crontinel?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most generic monitors tell you a job ran. They have no visibility into Laravel Horizon, queue depth, or whether your supervisor crashed. Crontinel reads the same Redis keys Horizon uses, so it catches failures the outside-in approach misses entirely."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does Crontinel require code changes?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "No. The Laravel package hooks into ScheduledTaskStarting, ScheduledTaskFinished, and ScheduledTaskFailed events automatically. You run composer require and the monitoring starts. No command wrapping, no custom metrics, no configuration required."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I self-host Crontinel?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. The package ships with a built-in dashboard at /crontinel that works entirely offline. The SaaS at app.crontinel.com is optional. Either way you own your data."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What alert channels does Crontinel support?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Slack, email, PagerDuty, and webhooks. Webhooks support HMAC signature verification. You can set different channels per monitor so critical jobs page PagerDuty while background tasks Slack."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>
  <Nav />

  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-16" id="main-content">

    <div class="text-center mb-14">
      <div class="inline-block text-xs font-semibold text-gray-400 bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full mb-4">
        Crontinel vs Laravel Telescope
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
        Telescope tells you what happened.<br class="hidden sm:block" /> Crontinel tells you <em class="text-green-400 not-italic">when something is wrong.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-gray-400 max-w-xl mx-auto">
        Laravel Telescope is a first-party debug assistant. It records requests, jobs, queries, and exceptions so you can inspect them. It's excellent at that job. But it doesn't alert you, it doesn't monitor thresholds, and it's not meant for production visibility.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-8 mb-16">

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What Telescope is for</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400">
          Telescope is a development and debugging tool. You install it in local or staging environments to inspect what your application is doing: which queries ran, which jobs fired, what the request lifecycle looked like. It's indispensable for development. The Laravel team built it well.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What Telescope is not</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
          Telescope is not a monitoring tool. It has no alerting, no thresholds, no concept of "this queue is too deep" or "this supervisor stopped." It records history you can browse; it does not watch for problems and notify you. If you enable it in production, you're adding overhead for a UI you only open after something breaks.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-gray-400">
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> No alerts of any kind (Slack, email, webhook)</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> No queue depth or Horizon supervisor monitoring</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> No configurable thresholds or failure rate tracking</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> No external visibility (requires VPN or internal access)</li>
          <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> Adds database writes for every request in production</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">The gap in a real scenario</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
          Your Horizon supervisor pauses at 2am. Jobs queue up. No one knows until a customer complains in the morning.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-gray-950 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">02:14</span> Horizon supervisor paused (reason unknown)</div>
          <div><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> Telescope: recorded the last job that ran before pause</div>
          <div><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> Telescope: no alert fired</div>
          <div><span class="text-red-400">✗</span> Telescope: queue depth unknown, no threshold to breach</div>
          <div class="pt-1 border-t border-gray-800 mt-1"></div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> <span class="text-green-400">Crontinel: alert fired at 02:14, supervisor paused</span></div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> Crontinel: Slack notification sent, on-call engineer paged</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-16">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-800 text-left">
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium">Capability</th>
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium text-center">Crontinel</th>
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium text-center">Telescope</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800/50">
          {[
            ['Slack / email alerts when something breaks', true, false],
            ['Horizon supervisor + paused state monitoring', true, false],
            ['Queue depth thresholds and alerts', true, false],
            ['Oldest pending job age', true, false],
            ['Failed jobs per minute with alerting', true, false],
            ['Scheduled job run history', true, true],
            ['Job payload and exception inspection', false, true],
            ['Query, request, log inspection', false, true],
            ['Works in production without overhead risk', true, false],
            ['External dashboard (no VPN needed)', true, false],
            ['Open source', true, true],
          ].map(([cap, ours, theirs]) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 text-gray-300">{cap}</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">{ours ? <span class="text-green-400">✓</span> : <span class="text-red-400">✗</span>}</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">{theirs ? <span class="text-green-400">✓</span> : <span class="text-red-400">✗</span>}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Use both, for different jobs</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-400">
        Telescope is a great development companion. Keep it in local and staging. Crontinel is your production watchdog. It alerts you before a customer does. They serve completely different purposes and there's no reason to choose between them.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-green-500/20 rounded-xl p-8 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Add alerting to your Laravel app</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-400 mb-6">
        Crontinel installs in two commands and starts monitoring Horizon and your scheduler immediately.
      </p>
      <div class="relative max-w-sm mx-auto mb-6">
        <div class="bg-gray-950 rounded-lg p-4 pr-14 font-mono text-sm text-green-400 text-left">
          <div>composer require crontinel/laravel</div>
          <div>php artisan crontinel:install</div>
        </div>
        <button role="button" aria-label="Copy to clipboard" onclick="navigator.clipboard.writeText('composer require crontinel/laravel\nphp artisan crontinel:install'); this.textContent='Copied!'; setTimeout(()=>this.textContent='Copy',1500)" class="absolute top-2 right-2 text-xs text-gray-400 hover:text-gray-300 bg-gray-800 hover:bg-gray-700 px-2 py-1 rounded transition-colors">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <a
        href="/#waitlist"
        class="inline-block bg-green-500 hover:bg-green-400 text-black font-semibold px-6 py-2.5 rounded transition-colors"
      >
        Start free
      </a>
    </div>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
